–1515","1503":"1503","1479":"1479","AFT 1487":"after 1487","1610":"1610","1533":"1533","1510":"1510","1487":"1487","1465":"1465","1475":"1475","1515":"1515","North Bowood, Dorset, England":"North Bowood, Dorset, England","Snails Croft, Dorset, England":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","North Bowood and Temple, Dorsetshire, England":"North Bowood, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Collins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Colin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish and Manx: shortened Anglicized from <b>Ó Coileáin</b>, compare   Cullen  , or in Man or west Ulster shortened from <b>Mac Coileáin</b>, compare   McQuillan   and   McCallion  . The genitival <i>-s</i> is a local addition to   Collin   and variants after the surname was Anglicized.","Americanized form of French   Colin   or   Collin   and also   Collette  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Colin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Alfredo, Francisco, Jesus, Ricardo, Alberto, Angel, Arturo, Eduardo, Esteban, Faustino.  French Alexandre, Andre, Armand, Georges, Henri, Jean Claude, Jean-Michel, Laurette, Lucien, Marcel, Patrice, Pierre.","French, Walloon, and Breton: from a French shortened pet form of the personal name   Nicolas   (see   Nicholas  ). This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","English: from the personal name <i>Colin</i>, a diminutive of <i>Col</i>, itself a pet form of   Nicholas  ."]},{"name":"Kolenc","meanings":["Slovenian:","topographic name derived from <i>koleno</i> ‘knee’.","nickname from the dialect plant name <i>kolenc</i> ‘yellow bedstraw (Galium verum)’ or ‘common nipplewort (Lapsana communis)’. Compare   Collins   3."]},{"name":"Callins","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Collins  ."]},{"name":"Collings","meanings":["English: variant of   Collins   or   Colling  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Collins was born in 1479, in Dorset, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Edward Collins. She had at least 2 sons with John Gallop. She died in 1510, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1479–1510":"1479–1510","1465–1533":"1465–1533","1487–1533":"1487–1533","1503–1610":"1